<br>
I used to be a news reporter and have had experience that gives me a different perspective on this subject.  I was a proponent of the death penalty until I had to sit in the courtroom and look into the eyes of the condemned man.  True, he was a murderer and should pay a serious penalty for his crimes, but when I looked at him and I could actually see that he was too a human being, it changed my whole perspective on it.  My husband and I totally disagree on this subject, but he hasn't had the life experience I have had to come to my decision. <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Quote the Raven...&quot;Nevermore&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries.showUserPublicProfile?gid=neonurd60>neonurd60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/3/02 4:26:55 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://unexplained-mysteries.netfirms.com/pi04.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Do you agree with the Death Penalty?</span><hr size=1> To me, it's not a question of punishment. Sitting in a cell for life would be, for me, worse than dying. <br>
It's not a question of deterrence. People who commit crimes think they'll get away with it, if they think at all.<br>
It's a question of whether or not I'm willing, as a prospective juror, to take the chance of a mad dog possibly getting free tokill again, even if the victim is another prisoner.<br>
