<br>
- Where the person chooses, consistently over at least a year, to die rather than be incarcerated<br>
<br>
- Where they have been released after a similar (capital) crime on the warning that a repeat offence will mean death, then reoffend and the proof is as conclusive as it can be<br>
<br>
- Where sufficient multiple offences of extreme crime (like child rape and murder) indicate the person can never be allowed free <br>
<br>
The big problems are:<br>
<br>
- It is difficult to argue that a civilised State should have the right to take life<br>
<br>
- No crime is 100% provable<br>
<br>
Being pragmatic you may think that the death penalty saves resources / money. That is not the US experience! On average it costs more state money to go through all the appeals etc on a death row prisoner than to incarcerate indefinitely. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theraven49>theraven49</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/4/02 11:42:10 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://unexplained-mysteries.netfirms.com/pi06.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: In principle, against, but</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- No crime is 100% provable<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
